text_clean: Joby Aviation, an electric air taxi developer backed by Toyota with $500 million in funding, is developing the Joby S4, an electric vertical take-off and landing (eVTOL) aircraft designed for urban and regional passenger transport. The aircraft accommodates one pilot and four passengers, has a range of up to approximately 240 kilometres, and achieves a cruising speed of around 320 km/h. It is expected to produce significantly lower noise emissions compared to helicopters. Pilot production of the Joby S4 is underway in Marina, California, and the company plans to open a second production facility in Dayton, Ohio, to enable manufacturing of four air taxis per month starting in 2027. Commercial operations are scheduled to begin in 2026, including in Dubai, pending final certification by the US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA). To support air taxi operations, Joby Aviation has partnered with Metropolis, the largest parking facility operator in the US, which manages over 4,200 locations and provides flight services at more than 350 sites. The partnership aims to develop 25 vertiports across the USA by repurposing existing Metropolis parking sites, with selection focused on markets identified as particularly attractive for initial electric air taxi deployment. The companies plan to integrate Metropolis’s technology—including biometrics, computer vision, and baggage handling services—into Joby’s air taxi operations to connect them with existing ground transportation infrastructure. As an initial step, Metropolis will provide its Bags VIP service to Blade Urban Air Mobility, Joby’s subsidiary, for helicopter flights between Manhattan and JFK or Newark airports in New York; these flights currently take five minutes and avoid up to two hours of traffic and typical airport delays. Air taxis are expected to replace helicopters in this service in the future.
